         <h1>John Adams, McCarthy Nemesis, Dies at 91 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>John G. Adams , a former general counsel for the Army whose repeated clashes with the anti-Communist crusader Joseph R. McCarthy in the early 1950 's ultimately helped bring him down , died today at his home in Dallas . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 91 . <br><blue>3</blue>Despite a long career in public service during five decades spent in Washington , Mr. Adams is best known for his confrontations with Senator McCarthy , the Wisconsin Republican who galvanized the nation in 1953 with hearings to root out supposed Communists in the armed forces . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Adams was a reluctant foil for McCarthy and his zealous aide Roy M. Cohn , who had prompted headlines with accusations that the Army 's Signal Corps laboratories at Fort Monmouth , N.J. , had been penetrated by traitors and spies . <br><blue>5</blue>McCarthy 's inquiries led to the suspension of 42 Army employees deemed to be '' security risks . '' <br><blue>6</blue>As general counsel , Mr. Adams had to deal with the bullying tactics of McCarthy and Cohn as they sought to make their case against workers at Fort Monmouth , an electronic research facility . <br><blue>7</blue>Appointed by Robert Stevens , Army secretary under President Dwight D. Eisenhower , to be a '' permanent liaison '' with the senator , Mr. Adams wrote in his memoirs that he understood his role was to seek a friendly , even '' fawning '' relationship with McCarthy . <br><blue>8</blue>But Mr. Adams 's efforts to ingratiate himself failed , and he became increasingly troubled by the senator 's threats and demands . <br><blue>9</blue>A case involving a Cohn friend later became central to the evidence that McCarthy had improperly interfered in the Army 's affairs . <br><blue>10</blue>In November 1953 , Pvt. G. David Schine , a close friend of Cohn , was drafted and assigned to Fort Dix , N.J . <br><blue>11</blue>According to Mr. Adams , Cohn had persistently sought to have Mr. Schine assigned to New York and had threatened to '' wreck the Army '' if he was ever sent overseas . <br><blue>12</blue>When Mr. Adams rejected such favoritism , McCarthy called a news conference and accused him of trying to use Mr. Schine as a bargaining chip to end the anti-Communist purge in the Army . <br><blue>13</blue>During the Army-McCarthy hearings , which were watched on television by millions of viewers for more than a month , Mr. Adams detailed McCarthy 's actions , adding to a growing public sense that the senator was out of control . <br><blue>14</blue>Much of Mr. Adams 's case against McCarthy was in written notes that painstakingly recorded the senator 's demands . <br><blue>15</blue>In his memoir , '' Without Precedent , '' Mr. Adams said he would not allow members of the Army Loyalty Board to submit to McCarthy 's questions . <br><blue>16</blue>The publication of a 40-page memorandum submitted by Mr. Adams prompted the hearings that ultimately led to the senator 's downfall . <br><blue>17</blue>McCarthy was censured by the Senate in 1954 ; he died an alcoholic three years later . <br><blue>18</blue>Mr. Adams did not emerge from the period unscathed . <br><blue>19</blue>He was temporarily removed from his job as general counsel after McCarthy filed formal charges against his superior , Secretary Stevens . <br><blue>20</blue>The episode haunted him , relatives said . <br><hr><br><blue>1(4)</blue>: <m_str>Cohn</m_str> (11_6) 	<m_str>Cohn</m_str> (6_17) 	<m_str>Cohn</m_str> (10_14) 	<m_str>Cohn</m_str> (9_5) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Adams 's case against McCarthy</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>A case involving a Cohn friend</m_str> (9_1) 	<br><blue>3(1)</blue>: <m_str>Washington</m_str> (3_13) 	<br><blue>4(9)</blue>: <m_str>the Army</m_str> (11_24) 	<m_str>the Army Loyalty Board</m_str> (15_19) 	<m_str>the Army</m_str> (1_10) 	<m_str>the Army 's</m_str> (4_24) 	<m_str>Army</m_str> (7_6) 	<m_str>the Army 's</m_str> (9_19) 	<m_str>the Army</m_str> (12_32) 	<m_str>the Army 's Signal</m_str> (4_24) 	<m_s